y, address this lacuna. Taking a variety of critical approaches, the contributors consider medieval definitions, paradigms andexperiences of female middle age, analysing how the middle-aged woman perceived herself subjectively, as well as how she was perceived by others. They seek to challenge the received wisdom that in the middle ages, at forty, womenwere deemed "old" and, from that point onwards, their thoughts should be focused on preparing for death. On the contrary, this collection demonstrates their energy, defiance and wit. Sue Niebrzydowski is Lecturer in English, Bangor University, Wales. Contributors: Jane Geddes, Clare A. Lees, Carol M. Meale, Anneke B. Mulder-Bakker, Sue Niebrzydowski, Raluca L. Radulescu, Sara Elin Roberts, Corinne Saunders, Diane Watt.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aMiddle-aged womenxHistoryyTo 1500. 4aMedieval History. 4aMedieval Literature. 4aWomen's & Gender Studies. 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh  aAnglo-Saxon.  aMiddle Ages.  adefiance.  aenergy.  amedieval period.  awit.  awomen.1 aGeddes, Jane, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLees, Clare A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLees, Clare, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMeale, Carol M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMeale, Carol, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMulder-Bakker, Anneke B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNiebrzydowski, Sue, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNiebrzydowski, Sue, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aRadulescu, Raluca L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRadulescu, Raluca, e